Assess Data

We see from the GSE info gotten, that the first half of the samples (first 9) were given high protein diets, and the other half (last 10) were given low diets.

Clean Data

We want to filter out the low counts and remove duplicates. We also want to plot the data to get more information.

#Genes count
dim(data)[1]
## [1] 28517
#Remove the low counts with edgeR
cpmData <- edgeR::cpm(data[2:19])
rownames(cpmData) <- data[,1]

keep <- rowSums(cpmData >1) >=10
filterData = data[keep,]

repeated <- filterData[duplicated(rownames(filterData)), ]

Map to HUGO

This data actually provided the HGNC gene symbols, so theres no need to convert. However, we will check it again to see if any do not match the HUGO format.

#Let's get the HGNC symbols and see how many of them matched to a gene symbol
ensembl <- biomaRt::useMart("ensembl")
ensembl_haspiens <- biomaRt::useDataset("hsapiens_gene_ensembl", mart=ensembl)
## Ensembl site unresponsive, trying asia mirror
symbolMatch <- biomaRt::getBM(attributes = "hgnc_symbol",
   filters = c("hgnc_symbol"),
   values = data$genesymbol,
   mart = ensembl_haspiens)

# Check the percentage unmatched
unmatch <- 1-dim(symbolMatch)[1]
percent <- (unmatch / dim(filterData)[1])*100

From the calculation, we see that around 26.95% of the given gene symbols are not in the expected HUGO format. However, there doesnt seem to be a way to match the old symbols, but they can still be found in the HUGO database.

Normalization

matrix <- as.matrix(filterData[,2:19])
rownames(matrix) <- filterData$hgnc_symbol
dValue <- edgeR::DGEList(counts=matrix, group=c(colnames(filterData)[2:19]))

#Get normalization factors
dValue <- edgeR::calcNormFactors(dValue)
normData <- edgeR::cpm(dValue)

#Pre-normalization
density <- apply(log2(edgeR::cpm(filterData[2:19])), 2, density)

xl <- 0
yl <- 0
for (i in 1:length(density)) {
  xlim <- range(c(xl, density[[i]]$x))
  ylim <- range(c(yl, density[[i]]$y))
}

plot(density[[1]], xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, ylab="density", xlab = "log2 CPM", main="Pre-normalization")
dCol<- cm.colors(length(density))
for (i in 1:length(density)){
  lines(density[[i]], col=dCol[i])
}

#After normalization
densityNorm <- apply(log2(normData), 2, density)

xl <- 0
yl <- 0
for (i in 1:length(densityNorm)) {
  xlim <- range(c(xl, densityNorm[[i]]$x))
  ylim <- range(c(yl, densityNorm[[i]]$y))
}

plot(densityNorm[[1]], xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, ylab="density", xlab = "log2 CPM", main="After normalization")
dCol<- cm.colors(length(densityNorm))
for (i in 1:length(densityNorm)){
  lines(densityNorm[[i]], col=dCol[i])
}

Document Questions

  1. What are the control and test conditions of the dataset?

This was a Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT) in which 19 patients with obesity undergoing bariatric surgery were randomized into 2 diet groups, a low protein (10E% protein) and a high protein (30E% protein), for three weeks prior to surgery. We are testing/comparing the RNA-seq analyses performed on liver samples (Intrahepatic lipid levels (IHL) and serum fibroblast growth factor 21 (FGF21)).

  1. Why is the dataset of interest to you?

Im interested in this dataset because Im interested in nutrition and its impact on our health.

  1. Were there expression values that were not unique for specific genes? How did you handle these?

There were not any, but there were some with too low values, and I did not include these.

  1. Were there expression values that could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols?

Yes, there was 26.95% of the values that couldnt be mapped.

  1. How many outliers were removed?

Based on the boxplot, it can be seen that the only those lower than 1 cpm, with a threshold of 10, were removed.
